<br>
<br>
Now that's plain silly.  I agree with Kreelos on this one.<br>
<br>
My character definitely looks down upon the evil races and classes and he sometimes demonstrates that prejudice.<br>
<br>
In RL, there are no races or professions that are inherently evil (well...with the possible exception of lawyers and politicians.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )  so I don't behave in a prejudiced fashion in RL....however, if I really thought that there was a class of people that were inherently evil (as some bigots and racists believe), I might also demonstrate prejudice in RL.  Fortunately, I was raised in a family in which acceptance of everyone was the norm.<br>
<br>
So...just because people play prejudiced characters, it doesn't follow that they are prejudiced in RL....it could mean that in some individual cases, but it is grossly inaccurate if you make it a sweeping generalization.<br>
<br>
Maybe your quote would be more accurate if you said, &quot;You know the old argument that if one is prejudiced in RL then one *probably* RP's as prejudiced, and if  one isn't prejudiced in RL then if one RP's a prejudiced character, it means they have real RP talent...because they can take on a role that is foreign to them&quot;.<br>
<br>
Personally, I think that being on the receiving end of prejudicial behavior in RL is what has made me accepting of others in RL, and what has enabled me to understand prejudice well enough to RP it convincingly in game. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sulissaurnvelve>Sulissa UrnVelve</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Almost dangerous<br>
